Node.js 22

This release formally introduces Node.js 22 support, which is officially tested and supported going forward.

If you wish to use Node.js 22 with Gatsby, we highly recommend using the latest 22.x release, as there are known issues with some older 22.x versions that Gatsby is unable to work around at this time.

Known Issue: gatsby develop fails with Node.js 22.7.0, 22.8.0, and 22.9.0

There is a critical bug in Node.js (nodejs/node#55145?) affecting versions 22.7.0, 22.8.0, and 22.9.0 that causes gatsby develop to fail with the error reported in gatsbyjs/gatsby#39068.

To avoid this, use Node.js 22.10.0 or later. (You can also use 22.6.0 or earlier.)

Known Issue: Page loads may hang in dev with experimental DEV_SSR enabled and Node.js 22.14.0 (or 20.19.0)

This will not affect most users.

A change landed in Node.js 20.19.0 and 22.14.0 results in requests to the gatsby develop dev server to occasionally hang for 15 seconds. This can only occur if you have opted in to the experimental DEV_SSR flag.

To avoid this, disable the experimental DEV_SSR flag. (You can also downgrade to Node.js 22.13.1 or earlier, 20.18.3 or earlier, or 18.x.)

items.title: Added Brainrot Shorts using Youtube Data API (With Backup Functionality for Devs without Key)
items.body:
Added Brainrot Shorts using Youtube Data API.

Notes:
The API Function is currently commented out/disabled since other people won't have the .env file. Said file will be shared if requested, but for now a dummy API key is in place, which will trigger the fallback/backup videos to play instead. This is sufficient for testing purposes.

If the .env file IS provided to you, place it in the root directory and edit the corresponding lines of code in Brainrot.jsx. The lines you need to comment/uncomment are marked with appropriate comments.

Brainrot.jsx component created.

Temporary Page called Brainrot. Short functionality can be relocated using

The API key is located on a private .env file. The key has 10000 requests a day.

Currently for testing, it contains 7 backup short videos, should suffice for now.

Youtube IFrames conflict with Swiper.js scrolling. This means that scrolling only works when the user is scrolling outside of the confines of the video. Inconvenient, but not as much of an issue on mobile.

Currently, shorts are autoplayed on mute. Most browsers require this. Currently looking into another API that bypasses this. This also creates a side-effect of the shorts playing audio even after scrolling past them. Will fix in a future update.
